I suggest using a _library_ instead of writing a serialization/deserialization routine from scratch. I find [cereal](https://github.com/USCiLab/cereal) really easy to use, maybe even easier than [boost::serialization](https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_71_0/libs/serialization/doc/index.html). It reduces the opportunity for bugs in your own code.

In your case I&#39;d go about serializing `double`s like this using cereal:

```cpp
#include &lt;cereal/archives/binary.hpp&gt;
#include &lt;fstream&gt;

int main() {
    std::ofstream outfile(&quot;test.bin&quot;, ios::binary);
    cereal::BinaryOutputArchive out(outfile);
    double x, y, z;
    x = y = z = 42.0;
    out(x, y, z);
}
```

To deserialize them you&#39;d use:

```cpp
#include &lt;cereal/archives/binary.hpp&gt;
#include &lt;fstream&gt;

int main() {
    std::ifstream infile(&quot;test.bin&quot;, ios::binary);
    cereal::BinaryInputArchive in(infile);
    double x,y,z;
    in(x, y, z);
}
```
You can also serialize/deserialize whole `std::vector&lt;double&gt;`s in the same fashion. Just add `#include &lt;cereal/types/vector.hpp&gt;` and use `in` / `out` like in the given example on a single `std::vector&lt;double&gt;` instead of multiple `double`s.

Ain&#39;t that swell.

---

**Edit**

In a comment you asked, _whether it&#39;d be possible to read a created binary file like that with Python._

_Answer:_

Serialized binary files aren&#39;t really meant to be very portable (things like endianness _could_ play a role here). You could easily adapt the example code I gave you to write a [JSON](http://uscilab.github.io/cereal/serialization_archives.html#json) file (another advantage of using a library) and [read that format in Python](https://docs.python.org/3.7/library/json.html).

Oh and `cereal::JSONOutputArchive` has an [option for setting precision](http://uscilab.github.io/cereal/assets/doxygen/classcereal_1_1JSONOutputArchive_1_1Options.html).

